[Thank you very much for an authoritative update on the background. The key
message is "this is an interesting example on how a dangerous parasite can
establish itself to a new area after accidental introduction of an
intermediate host".
Professor Henttonen refers to 2 studies on serological screening. In the
1994 paper 7 884 persons were investigated for _E. multilocularis_ specific
antibodies and 289 were positive and were retested. In the retest, 152 were
positive and 140 underwent clinical examination and ultrasound/computerized
tomography of the liver and 12 cases were found. These results are very
close to the Japanese results where the end result was that approximately
5% of seropositives had clinical disease. It is important to realize that
imaging of the liver has a lower resolution so a normal
ultrasound/computerized tomography does not rule out infection.
The second study reports screening with ultrasound and a variety of
antigens in Bavaria, Germany. Two cases were found by ultrasound screening
of which one was totally seronegative (but only positive by PCR on biopsy
material) and 5 tested positive against at least 2 antigens. The conclusion
must still be that the predictive value of a positive test is at best
uncertain and will lead to repeated testing of people. Perhaps the
conclusion should be that until the serological tests are better,
population screening should be restricted to ultrasound alone. -Mod. EP
..........................ep/ds
